\title{cptkirk: Warp-Speed Remote GDAL Warping of Cloud-Optimised GeoTIFFs}
\description{
A remote, overview-aware \code{gdalwarp}. cptkirk works out which source pixels a
requested warp will touch, streams only those tiles over the Rust
\href{https://github.com/developmentseed/async-tiff}{async-tiff} reader (high
remote-read saturation, at the appropriate overview level), stages them as an
in-memory GDAL source, then hands the actual reprojection and resampling to
GDAL via \code{gdalraster} --- following the \code{gdalwarp} argument interface.
}
\section{Warping}{

Two entry points onto the same engine:
\itemize{
\item \code{\link[=ck_warp]{ck_warp()}} --- the recommended, batteries-included helper: named
\code{t_srs} / \code{te} / \code{tr} / \code{ts} / \code{r} / \code{bands} arguments plus cptkirk's
performance defaults (multi-threading, generous warp memory and cache,
\code{SKIP_NOSOURCE}, band-subset streaming).
\item \code{\link[=warp_remote]{warp_remote()}} --- a faithful, defaults-free sibling of
\code{\link[gdalraster:warp]{gdalraster::warp()}}: same \code{src} / \code{dst} / \code{t_srs} / \code{cl_arg} call shape,
but the source is streamed remotely. Forwards \code{cl_arg} to GDAL verbatim.
\item \code{\link[=ck_read]{ck_read()}} --- \code{\link[=ck_warp]{ck_warp()}} that returns the result as an R matrix/array
instead of writing a file, for quick extraction and inspection.
}
}

\section{Stacking and batch}{

The same engine drives many sources through one saturating pool:
\itemize{
\item \code{\link[=ck_stack]{ck_stack()}} / \code{\link[=ck_stack_read]{ck_stack_read()}} --- fetch one window from N sources and
write (or return) them as separate bands of a single output: the
\code{gdalbuildvrt -separate} analogue, as opposed to the mosaic \code{\link[=ck_warp]{ck_warp()}}
makes from multiple sources.
\item \code{\link[=ck_batch]{ck_batch()}} --- reproject/resample a whole list of groups (e.g. a STAC
item list, one group per acquisition) through ONE connection pool and ONE
streaming fetch, writing one file per band or one stacked file per group.
The output mirrors the structure of the input.
}
}

